{"altmetric_id":14548907,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":17,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":24},"blogs":{"unique_users_count":1,"unique_users":[56272],"posts_count":1},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":18,"unique_users":["GreenJournal","ineurocienciasa","Cefaleasclinico","CadillacLade12","barca_emanuele","lisahobsonwebb","HannahPradeep","NatRevNeurol","docile_atom","DrFarhanSubhani","InsermU930","paulwalters1989","ShawnParker2013","LehmannHC","PabloCabezudo","JMEscoffre31","jmankin","bowser_bna"],"posts_count":20},"facebook":{"unique_users_count":2,"unique_users":["1695318340726330","202556649324"],"posts_count":2},"googleplus":{"unique_users_count":1,"unique_users":["Jes\u00fas Porta-Etessam"],"posts_count":1}},"selected_quotes":["Sonography has high diagnostic value in treatment-naive chronic inflammatory neuropathies","important study #neurology"],"citation":{"abstract":"To determine the diagnostic value of high-resolution ultrasound (HRUS) for detection of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (CIDP), Lewis-Sumner syndrome (LSS), and multifocal motor neuropathy (MMN).\nBetween January 2013 and January 2015, we enrolled 75 consecutive treatment-naive patients with chronic inflammatory neuropathies and 70 disease controls. We performed extensive nerve conduction and standardized HRUS studies bilaterally of large arm and leg nerves and brachial plexus. We determined optimal sonographic cutoff values of nerve size and used receiver operating characteristic analysis and logistic regression models to identify nerve combinations with optimal diagnostic performance.\nEnlargement of median nerve at forearm >10 mm(2), upper arm >13 mm(2), and any trunk of brachial plexus >8 mm(2) was 99% specific for chronic inflammatory neuropathies. A shortened HRUS protocol for detecting this abnormal nerve enlargement showed high sensitivity (83%-95%), positive predictive value (100%), and negative predictive value (98%) in discriminating CIDP, LSS, and MMN from clinical mimics.\nSonographic enlargement of proximal median nerve segments in the arms and brachial plexus is a key feature of chronic inflammatory neuropathies, which helps to reliably distinguish them from axonal neuropathies and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.\nThis study provides Class II evidence that, in absence of clinical features that suggest a hereditary demyelinating neuropathy, sonographic enlargement of proximal median nerve segments and brachial plexus accurately identifies patients with chronic inflammatory neuropathies.","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa5ea3cf058f610005b59","authors":["H. Stephan Goedee","W. Ludo van der Pol","Jan-Thies H. van Asseldonk","Hessel Franssen","Nicolette C. Notermans","Alexander J.F.E. Vrancken","Michael A. van Es","Stavros Nikolakopoulos","Leo H. Visser","Leonard H. van den Berg"],"doi":"10.1212\/wnl.0000000000003483","endpage":"151","first_seen_on":"2016-12-08T04:41:41+00:00","funders":["niehs"],"issns":["1526-632X","0028-3878"],"issue":"2","journal":"Neurology","last_mentioned_on":1495274610,"links":["http:\/\/www.neurology.org\/content\/early\/2016\/12\/07\/WNL.0000000000003483.short?rss=1&utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter","http:\/\/www.neurology.org\/content\/early\/2016\/12\/07\/WNL.0000000000003483.short?rss=1","http:\/\/neurology.org\/lookup\/doi\/10.1212\/WNL.0000000000003483","http:\/\/www.neurology.org\/content\/88\/2\/143.abstract","http:\/\/www.neurology.org\/content\/early\/2016\/12\/07\/WNL.0000000000003483.short?rss=1&utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=gplus","http:\/\/www.neurology.org\/cgi\/content\/short\/88\/2\/143","https:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/27927940?dopt=Abstract"],"pdf_url":"http:\/\/www.neurology.org\/content\/early\/2016\/12\/07\/WNL.0000000000003483.full.pdf","pmid":"27927940","pubdate":"2016-12-07T00:00:00+00:00","publisher_subjects":[{"name":"Clinical Sciences","scheme":"era"},{"name":"Neurosciences","scheme":"era"},{"name":"Cognitive Science","scheme":"era"}],"scopus_subjects":["Medi